We have<br><br>kx + y + z = 1<br><br>x + ky + z = k<br><br>x + y + kz = k<sup>2</sup><br><br>For no solution $$\left| {\matrix{
   k &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; k &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; k  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow k({k^2} - 1) - 1(k - 1) + 1(1 - k) = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {k^3} - k - k + 1 + 1 - k = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {k^3} - 3k + 2 = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow (k + 2)(k - 1)(k - 1) = 0 \Rightarrow k = 1, - 2$$<br><br>But for k = 1, first two equations will be identical.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ k = $$-$$ 2

Let $$\phi (x) = f(x) - g(x)$$<br><br>$$ = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {x,} &amp; {x\,is\,rational\,number}  \cr 
   { - x,} &amp; {x\,is\,irrational\,number}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>For one-one, <br><br>Take any straight line parallel to X-axis which will intersect $$\phi$$(x) only at one point.<br><br>So, $$\phi$$(x) is one-one.<br><br>For onto, as $$\phi$$(x)<br><br>$$ = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {x,} &amp; {x\,is\,rational\,number}  \cr 
   { - x,} &amp; {x\,is\,irrational\,number}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>Which shows y = x and y = $$-$$x for rational and irrational values<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ y $$\in$$Real number<br><br>$$\therefore$$ Range = codomain<br><br>so, $$\phi$$(x) is onto<br><br>Thus, (f $$-$$ g) is one-one and onto.

We have,<br><br>$$A = \left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 
   2 &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right]$$ and $$B = \left[ {\matrix{
   2 &amp; 3  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; { - 2}  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$AB = \left[ {\matrix{
   {1 \times 2 + ( - 1) \times ( - 1)} &amp; {1 \times 3 + ( - 1) \times ( - 2)}  \cr 
   {2 \times 2 + 3 \times ( - 1)} &amp; {2 \times 3 + 3 \times ( - 2)}  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$ = \left[ {\matrix{
   3 &amp; 5  \cr 
   1 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$BA = \left[ {\matrix{
   2 &amp; 3  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; { - 2}  \cr 

 } } \right]\left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 
   2 &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right] = \left[ {\matrix{
   8 &amp; 7  \cr 
   { - 5} &amp; { - 5}  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>Clearly, AB $$\ne$$ BA<br><br>Now, AB (A<sup>$$-$$1</sup> B<sup>$$-$$1</sup>) = AB (BA)<sup>$$-$$1</sup> [$$\because$$ (AB)<sup>$$-$$1</sup> = B<sup>$$-$$1</sup> A<sup>$$-$$1</sup>]<br><br>AB (BA)<sup>$$-$$1</sup> is a unit matrix if and only if AB = BA but AB $$\ne$$ BA. So, AB (A<sup>$$-$$1</sup> B<sup>$$-$$1</sup>) is not a unit matrix. Since, AB $$\ne$$ BA, therefore (AB)<sup>$$-$$1</sup> $$\ne$$ A<sup>$$-$$1</sup> B<sup>$$-$$1</sup>.
